body:
The main go compilers only support `linux/mips64` and `linux/mips64le` 

For MIPS32 you'd have to use gccgo which I don't have much experience with.

Fancy working out how to do it?
Here would be the place to start: https://github.com/golang/go/wiki/GccgoCrossCompilation

Hello, I have no experience with go , but yes with C/C++ on MIPS / PIC / ARM... and other embedded platforms with crosscompiling tools.

Maybe I can try port your code, but the following two weeks I'm a bit busy because my PhD.

It shouldn't need any sort of porting, just building the right cross compiler.

I think go 1.9 (out in about 9 months) may have native support for MIPS32.

Unexpectedly (to me anyway) mips32 support will be in go 1.8 which is in beta right now.  I attempted to compile a version for you to try but failed due to: https://github.com/golang/go/issues/18192  - I'm sure it will work soon though!

I was able to compile other go based tool to access to g drive under 1.8 "beta" for mips32 le  ([gdrive](https://github.com/prasmussen/gdrive/issues/219)), maybe it needs some patches on the dependencies, I will try the same with rclone :D
It's not going to run on typical OpenWRT routers, see https://github.com/golang/go/issues/17984

@jech On two routers that I have with openwrt /padavan/tomato (RT-N56U and xiaomi mi router) both are based on  MT762x  ( MIPS 24KEc V5.0 and MIPS 1004Kc)

I was able to crosscompile the latest master branch of golang for MIPS 32 LE and it works propertly at least with gdrive source code, just download my binaries and test ( MIPS 32 LE cpu only)....

I don't know if the compiled result is not using emulated FPU/HW FPU, but it works....

Maybe you need to patch some dependencies in order to recognise MIPSLE on build as mips32... I had to do it with soniakeys that is a dependency of gdrive.

The only thing that I have to solve now is about the root certificates that are missing in case of tomato FW.

**EDIT**: Both of my routers seems that includes [FPU](https://wikidevi.com/wiki/MIPS32#MIPS32_1004Kc_.2F_1004Kf) , so I'm not able to test the crosscompile on "SW-FPU"
I'm pretty confident that we'll have rclone building for mips32 quite soon. I don't know exactly what hardware is supported by the go runtime though.

@ncw I think that @jech  assumes like me that all MIPS32 based routers includes or not FPU.

My case, it includes FPU, maybe the routers that he's working on, doesn't includes fpu.

@alecuba16, I'm fairly positive that the 24KEc and 1004Kc cores have no FPU â€” it's the 24Kf and the 1004Kf that do.  I'm glad to hear that Go binaries work for you, I'd be interested to know the explanation.

@jech 
About the cpu, as far as I know the RT-N56U has mediatek MIPS 1004Kc or 74Kc depending on revision, mine's is V1. In the case of this asus the official datasheet [ shows a FPU on second page](http://www.bdti.com/MyBDTI/pubs/74k.pdf) 

The xiaomi router , has mediatek with MT7620A that seems to be 24KEc that doesn't have HW FPU , but it runs too, so the only possibilities that I'm thinking now:

a)-Master of go compiler supports FPU emulation or is supported by some hack-kernel emulator.

b)-The gdrive code and its dependencies doesn't do any FPU compute, that is mostly improbable because it uses https, graph algorithms,and other dependencies that for sure there are floats... 

c)-The binary runs, lists files and help, but since I have no tested the connecting part because I have to integrate the root certificates on tomato, the code part that uses FPU was still not invoked. This is because I have to fix the requirements for https connection (root certificates). Anyway I can test on openwrt first that is easier to integrate the root certificates.

Anyway if you want and you have root certificates installed, you can test my binaries for gdrive (sorry for the intrusion, just for testing purposes):

MIPS32be (big endian) : https://mega.nz/#!w59x2BIR!-A0bSwkqW-KCN-yZxrSw9r_17uSXwTHL9Jz1xEydKU4

MIPS32le (little endian): 
https://mega.nz/#!Eh0EwYaZ!8-qQgtEW3kXPSEoRQHhG5mk3QZ0VECxGyjeLuenlzoc

Tomorrow I will compile a simple float operation and will try if it works.
Most probably your kernel has been compiled with the FPU emulator included.

OK the upstream golang/x/sys repo is fixed (swift work Go team!) so here are some binaries for mips and mipsle built with go 1.8beta1

  * mips - http://pub.rclone.org/rclone-v1.34-49-ge79a5de-mips.zip
  * mipsle - http://pub.rclone.org/rclone-v1.34-49-ge79a5de-mipsle.zip

Check out [how to install root certs also](http://rclone.org/faq/#rclone-gives-x509-failed-to-load-system-roots-and-no-roots-provided-error)

I'd be interested to know if these work!

rclone definitely uses floating point maths for the stats calculations BTW.

Do I need to build both mips and mipsle builds?  Are they both in use?

I think that the most common is little endian,so if I would have to choice, little endian always, but there are Big endian routers...

https://dev.openwrt.org/wiki/platforms

Thanks for the root certs link :)
